<hl>
<seg id=1> The Thailand Financial Minister Talin left for Japan to negotiate for revival loans for the economy. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Bangkok) The Thailand Financial Minister Talin left for Tokyo yesterday for the discussion on Thailand's 30 billion US dollars (48.6 billion new Yuan) compound fund, which is provided by Japan for relieving the financial crisis in the Asian economic system. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said that, during the 4 days spent visiting in Japan, he will go deep into the discussions. However, he can not predict how much money Japan is going to promise for Thailand. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Talin told the reporters at Bangkok International Airport: " I have already explained to Premier Chuanlupei about how the loan will be used. However, we did not come up with the actual amount of the loan, as Japan has not yet informed us." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He said that he hopes to get a low interest and generous amortization plan for this loan. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> He said that, he is going to have meetings with the Japanese officials of the Trade Bureau to discuss the new assistance for Thailand's industrial and agricultural reorganization. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The Japanese Financial Minister, Kongzhesiyi announced the 30 billion US dollar compound fund at the Seven Countries Group Meeting on October 3. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In a short period of time, Japan will distribute 15 billion US dollars for assistance in specific areas such as trade and finance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Japan will provide direct financial assistance by providing Import & Export Bank loans and by purchasing Asian public bonds, and will also provide Japanese currency loans for Asian countries to assist in their development. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It will also sponsor bank loans in Asian countries and issue Asian public bonds, and help other Asian countries with their international fundraising. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Kongzhesiyi's  package plan of assistance is extremely important to Thailand, as Thailand has just issued 500 million US dollars of global public bonds last month. </seg>
<seg id=12> Thailand plans to use the money to increase working capital and stimulate the economy. </seg>
<seg id=13> Thailand's economy has been suffering from high cost loans and the new global financial market crisis. </seg>
</p>
